close_symbols: Linker / exported-symbol map / API registration tables
explanation:
Explain why each symbol is required to decide whether OS_DirectoryRewind is dead code:

- OS_ObjectIdGetById: This is the first call inside OS_DirectoryRewind. You must inspect its side effects (global state, error handling, resource accounting, callbacks) because if OS_ObjectIdGetById performs observable actions, removal of OS_DirectoryRewind may change program behaviour even if OS_DirectoryRewind appears only to forward a call.

- OS_DirRewind_Impl: The wrapper delegates to this implementation when the ID check succeeds. Determine whether OS_DirRewind_Impl has observable effects (I/O, state changes) so that removing OS_DirectoryRewind (and thus calls into the impl) would alter behaviour.

- OS_ObjectIndexFromToken: Called (transitively) by OS_DirRewind_Impl per the call graph. Needed to understand whether token conversion/index lookup has side effects that make the wrapper meaningful beyond a simple no-op.

- OS_ObjectIdTransactionInit, OS_ObjectIdToArrayIndex, OS_ObjectIdConvertToken, OS_ObjectIdTransactionCancel: These are callees of OS_ObjectIdGetById (per the call graph). They must be examined to see if the ID-get logic performs transactions, locking, accounting, or other observable actions; such side effects mean the wrapper is not dead even if it only performs the check.

- UT_Stub_RegisterReturnType, UT_Stub_RegisterContextWithMetaData, UT_ExecuteBasicHandler, UT_Stub_GetReturnValuePtr: These appear in the static call graph for the target (likely due to test harness stubs or instrumentation). If the compiled binary or test harness contains these stub interactions tied to OS_DirectoryRewind (e.g., for test-time registration or behavior injection), they represent observable activities or test-side effects that must be considered when deciding if the function is dead in the delivered build or test builds.

- All_callers_of_OS_DirectoryRewind (link-time references / cross-reference): To classify a function as dead code you must prove there are no call sites (including indirect calls via function pointers). The explicit set of callers (from the full project cross-reference / symbol table) is therefore required; the static graph here lists no callers, but a full project-wide symbol/linker check is needed to be certain.

- Linker / exported-symbol map / API registration tables: Functions can be referenced indirectly (exported API table, syscall/dispatch tables, or by name from other modules or dynamic loaders). Check the linker export table and any API/dispatch registration structures to ensure OS_DirectoryRewind is not referenced externally (e.g., by dynamically-loaded modules, command interpreters, or stub registration). Such external references would make the function live even if no direct callers exist in the static call graph.

In summary: inspect the immediate callees and their transitive effects to determine whether the function body performs any observable actions, and inspect all external references/callers (direct and indirect via export/registration tables) to determine whether removing the function would alter program behaviour.
